properties.Name:
Imperial Oil Resources, Cold Lake
Cold Lake Operations - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: From Wikimapia: 'This is the area where Imperial Oil has their cyclic steam stimulation (CSS) operations. Bitumen removed from the wellpads here is diluted and transported south to the US on the Primrose Pipeline. With the startup of the nearby Mahikan North and Nabiye phases, the operation now has the capacity to produce 170,000 barrels per day of bitumen.'

properties.Name:
Shell Canada Limited, Athabasca
Jackpine Mine - Strip mine - Operating
properties.Notes: This is a three-way operation, Shell (60%), Chevron (20%) and Marathon (20%). It's your classic stip mine with an upgrader to produce synthetic crude that's refined into gasoline down south. Currently under consideration is an expansion of the Jackpine site, which has received the go-ahead from Canadian regulators.

properties.Name:
Connacher Oil and Gas Limited, Athabasca
Great Divide - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: This upstart company secured massive investment and has a billion dollars in debt. They were using steam to flush out bitumen at two sites advertised as gold mines. Operations are being curtailed in early 2016 as rock-bottom oil prices destroy what was always a bad idea.

properties.Name:
Husky Energy, Athabasca
Sunrise - Steam injection mine - Approved
properties.Notes: It's a 50/50 joint venture with BP. More like sunset than sunrise given current oil prices - but unfortunately that could change.

properties.Name:
Canadian Natural Resources Limited (CNRL), Athabasca
Horizon Mine - Strip mine - Operating
properties.Notes: It's another strip mine with an upgrader to produce synthetic crude, ugghhh.

properties.Name:
MEG Energy Corp., Athabasca
Christina Lake Regional Project - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: This is a melt-it-and-pump-it operation, producing dilbit (diluted bitumen) rather than synthetic crude oil.

properties.Name:
OSUM Oil Sands Corp., Cold Lake
Orion - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: OSUM is a private equity operation headed by a former Suncor backed by Warburg Pincus, Blackstone Group, BlackRock, Kern Partners, as well as Korea Investment Corp. In 2014 they bought this site from Shell with a 225 million USD loan from Barclays and Goldman Sachs (source). Just as in the 2008 real-estate debacle, we're looking at financially driven overproduction and damn the consequences.

properties.Name:
Cenovus FCCL Ltd., Athabasca
Foster Creek - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes:
Cenovus is an 'Imagine Canada Caring' company. Well, what they're doing to the atmosphere makes it hard to imagine.

ConocoPhilips has a 50% stake in this operation and in two other Cenovus oil sands projects (source.

properties.Name:
Husky Energy, Cold Lake
Tucker - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: Husky has 100% ownership of these holes in the earth. Pictured are the steam generators, complete with some quasi-Soviet heroic figures. The forward march of industry goes ever onward.

properties.Name:
Japan Canada Oil Sands Limited (JACOS), Athabasca
Hangingstone - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes:
JACOS was one of the developers of the steam-assisted gravity drainage process (SAGD), which is the way most tar sands bitumen is taken out of the ground. Bsically they inject steam down one hole and pump up the pooling bitumen from a slightly deeper nearby well. One reason tar sands oil is so nuts is that it takes a huge quantity of natural gas to heat the steam....

Meanwhile, Enbridge is building a 33 mile pipeline to carry 40,000 barrels of dilbit a day to some petcoke pile near you.

properties.Name:
Imperial Oil Resources, Athabasca
Kearl Mine - Strip mine - Operating
properties.Notes: ExxonMobil has a 30% stake in the Kearl project, which apparently has some pretty dubious labor practices, not to mention the environmentals (which they claim are as green as the local forest used to be).

properties.Name:
Nexen Energy, aka China National Offshore Oil Corporation, Athabasca
Long Lake - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: Over 1.3 million gallons leaked from a pipeline carrying bitumen, water and sand on this site. The leak was discovered by a contractor on June 15, 2015. Estimates of how long it may have been leaking range up to two weeks. So far it appears to be the largest pipeline leak in the Tar Sands.

properties.Name:
Suncor Energy Inc., Athabasca
Mackay River - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: Suncor took over the former state-owned company Petro-Canada, to become a full-on oil major with drilling operations and distribution. They are the largest producer of tar sands bitumen.

properties.Name:
ConocoPhillips Canada Resources Limited, Athabasca
Surmont - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: The sprawling steam plant is a 50/50 joint venture with Total E&P Canada.

properties.Name:
Canadian Natural Resources Limited (CNRL), Cold Lake
Primrose, Wolf and Burnt Lakes - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.EPA: Wikipedia entry seems to be written by the company, don't bother.
properties.Notes: 'Throughout 2013 and extending into early 2014, four uncontrolled releases of bitumen have been occurring at Canadian Natural Resources Limiteds (CNRLs) high pressure cyclic steam stimulation (HPCSS) Primrose operations near Cold Lake, Alberta. Similar large and uncontrolled releases occurred in 2006 and 2009. The HPCSS method (also referred to as 'huff and puff') involves repeated cycles of steam injection, followed by 'soaking' of the steam and bitumen, and then extraction of the bitumen emulsion to the surface via a single well bore. In addition to reducing the viscosity of the bitumen, the method results in deformation, fracturing of bedrock, and vertical heave' (source.

properties.Name:
Canadian Natural Resources Limited (CNRL), Athabasca
Kirby Lake - Pilot in situ - Approved

Shell Canada Limited, Athabasca
Muskeg River Mine - Strip mine - Operating
properties.Notes: It's a joint venture on a strip mine, split between Shell Canada (60%), Marathon Oil Canada (20%) and Chevron Canada (20%). The bitumen goes to the Scotford Upgrader in Fort Saskatchewan where it's made into synthetic crude. To experience the way they want you to think about all this, watch a truly asinine Shell propaganda video about this site here. At the same time, Shell is developing a Quest Carbon Capture process that injects liquified CO2 deep into the earth, in an effort to shrink the carbon footprint that their endeavor - and our consumption - is so dramatically increasing. The disjunct between these two messages says a lot about the world we live in.

properties.Name:
Pengrowth Corporation, Cold Lake
Lindbergh - Steam injection mine - Operating
properties.Notes: This oil and gas company, like a number of others, made a neoliberal move to escape taxes and pay tremendous benefits to its so-called trustees (up to 15% on invested capital) until finally the Canadian government cracked down. Here's how it worked: 'These companies, originally structured as Canadian royalty trusts (CANROYs), are oil and natural gas producers. As trusts, they didn't pay federal income taxes if they distributed their income to shareholders. The resulting double-digit dividend yields grabbed dividend investors attention in the mid-2000s. Eventually the government cracked down and starting in 2011, trusts were required to pay the same taxes as regular corporations. Consequently, all trusts converted to corporations, and many cut their dividends' (source). That's the sort of profit scheme that has made the Midwest into a bull's eye for the most toxic petroleum on earth.

STP McKay - Steam injection mine - Operating

properties.Name:
Petrobank Energy and Resources Ltd., Peace River #2
Dawson Pilot Project - Pilot in situ - Stopped
properties.Notes: This company is thankfully defunct. Its business model depended on a technique to pump air underground and start combustion to melt the oil, instead of using steam. The idea was that you could 'crack' the oil underground and produce an upgraded crude beneath the surface. Apparently it never worked: one experiment was stopped midway when smoke was detected in a distant formation. The entire Tar Sands story is Promethean. This one goes to extremes.

properties.Name:
Suncor Energy Inc., Athabasca
Dover - Steam injection mine - Approved
properties.Notes: In this case they are trying to develop something called 'Enhanced Solvent Extraction Incorporating Electromagnetic Heating,' which is a way of using the well casing as an antenna for radio waves that warm the bitumen to 160 Fahrenheit, before solvent is pumped in to finish liquefying it (with high-pressure steam, it's heated to almost 400 degrees). The advantage is to use no water. The test is backed by lots of partners: Devon, Nexen Energy ULC, Suncor, Harris Corporation, with funding in part from the Climate Change and Emissions Management Corporation. Clearly the industry is interested.

properties.Notes: This is the site where the exploitation of the tar sands got started, courtesy of a great American philanthropist: 'Commercial production of oil from the Athabasca oil sands began in 1967, with the opening of the Great Canadian Oil Sands (GCOS) plant in Fort McMurray. It was the first operational oil sands project in the world, owned and operated by the American parent company, Sun Oil Company. When the $US240 million-dollar plant officially opened with a capacity of 45,000 bpd, it marked the beginning of commercial development of the Athabasca oil sands. In 2013 McKenzie-Brown listed industrialist J. Howard Pew as one of the six visionaries who built the Athabasca oil sands. By the time of his death in 1971, the Pew family were ranked by Forbes magazine as one of the half-dozen wealthiest families in America. The Great Canadian Oil Sands Limited (then a subsidiary of Sun Oil Company but now incorporated into an independent company known as Suncor Energy Inc.) produced 30,000 barrels per day (4,800 m3/d) of synthetic crude oil' (from the Wikipedia entry on Athabascan Oil Sands).
